Research library and dependency usage anti-patterns detectable by static analysis, covering both security-adjacent quality issues and pure quality concerns. Document the following categories: using deprecated API calls that have documented replacements, importing standard library modules when a safer or more idiomatic alternative exists (e.g., os.system vs subprocess, pickle for untrusted data, md5 for security-sensitive hashing), using library features in ways that are known to be performance-inefficient (e.g., appending to strings in a loop vs join, using list comprehension where a generator would suffice in memory-constrained contexts), and importing entire large libraries when only a small submodule is needed (lazy import anti-patterns). For Python specifically, research the bandit security linter's rule set for library misuse and the flake8-bugbear plugin rules. For JavaScript, research the eslint-plugin-security rules and the eslint recommendations around dangerous APIs. Research how tools identify which version of a library introduced a deprecation or removal, and how they handle the case where the same symbol is available from multiple sources. Cover the lazy import pattern specifically: when is a top-level import a quality problem (slowing startup time significantly) versus acceptable? Find any empirical research on the startup time impact of eager versus lazy imports in large Python applications. Document the detection approach for identifying lazy import candidates based on call site frequency and import cost.
